ese decisions, how they became powerful, and why they are only slightly closer today than a decade ago to protecting the public from disasters. Tracing the intertwined development of disaster expertise, public policy, and urbanization over the past century, historian Scott Gabriel Knowles tells the fascinating story of how this diverse collection of professionals—insurance inspectors, engineers, scientists, journalists, public officials, civil defense planners, and emergency managers—emerged as the authorities on risk and disaster and, in the process, shaped modern America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDisaster reliefvResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aDisaster reliefxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDisasterszUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aDisasterszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEmergency managementvResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aEmergency managementzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aHazard mitigationvResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aHazard mitigationxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRisk assessmentzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aRisk assessmentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGeneral.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aSocial Science.  aUrban Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/97808122